fields.detail:
Good Job!

You just navigated to your project board and opened this card! Check out the other cards on the board for more info.

fields.summary:
Edit/View a card

Click the pencil icon in the upper right hand of this card.
fields.detail:
Good Job!

You just opened the detail window for this card.  From here you can see everything about it.  If you click around on it, you could edit it, go ahead and explore it a bit.

A card represents a unit of work in ScrumDo.  For teams doing Scrum, they are usually User Stories.  If you are brand new to Scrum, take a look at our Beginners Guide.

All of the cards in this tutorial project have more information if you open them.

When you're done with this card, feel free to close or save this window with the buttons in the upper right.

fields.summary:
Move Cards

You can drag these cards into the columns on the right to track what is happening with them.
fields.detail:
There are a couple other ways to move cards:

  • The dropdown on the right of this window.
  • By shift-clicking several cards on the board and then using the move-card button in the toolbar (the grid of squares).

fields.summary:
Sub Tasks

A lot of teams will create Sub Tasks on their user stories.  Open this card to see how.
fields.detail:
See the "Tasks" button at the top of this window?  That will open a mini-board where you can create and manage the sub tasks for this card.

If you want to see your sub tasks on your main board, open up the board editor (see the next card) and make one of the columns a Task Column.

You can set up your task statuses in your project settings.

fields.summary:
Customize your project

Click the "Settings" button at the top of your board to customize all aspects of your project.
fields.detail:
Within that, you can find the "Board Editor" that lets you change how this board looks to match your team's workflow.

When you're done with this tutorial project, you'll also find the Delete option in there under Admin Options

fields.summary:
Create a card

There are several ways to create a card, the easiest is the dropdown menu at the top of each column on your board.
fields.detail:
Some other ways:
  • Open your backlog panel on the left and use the quick-add form at the top.
  • Open the card-list view of an iteration from the navigation panel on the right and use the quick-add form at the top of that page.

  • Create a new card from the Planning tool
  • Import cards via Excel
  • Import GitHub issues via our integration

fields.summary:
Backlog

Your backlog is where future work not currently being worked on goes.
fields.detail:
Open the panel on the left to get a miniature view of your backlog right from your board.

Or you can click on "Backlog" in the right navigation panel to go to your full backlog.

fields.summary:
Getting Help

Click the Gear menu in the upper right corner and choose Help/Support to ask us anything.
fields.detail:
We have some guides available at: http://help.scrumdo.com/help/

You can also email us: support@scrumdo.com

fields.summary:
Create an Iteration

You're looking at a default iteration we made for you.  You can create a new one by clicking the "Add Iteration" button that is inside the Navigation panel on the right.
fields.detail: If you're doing Scrumban or Kanban with continuous flow, leave the dates blank.  As cards are completed and no longer needed, you can archive them to keep things tidy.

fields.summary:
Planning Tool

The planning tool lets you create Epics to categorize your cards, and to plan out your iterations.
fields.detail: Click on Planning in the right navigation bar to get to it.

fields.summary:
Invite Other People

You can invite other people via 'Teams' from your organization dashboard.
fields.detail: Teams also define the access people have and what projects they can access.

fields.summary: Create a ScrumDo Trial
fields.detail: Since you're seeing this, you have already completed this one!

fields.summary:
Reports

Track your progress in your project with reports.
fields.detail: Click the Reports link in the right navbar. There are a couple days of sample data in this project.

fields.summary:
Edit Iteration

You can change the name or dates of an iteration by going into the card list view and clicking Iteration Settings at the top.
fields.detail: That is also where you can delete or archive iterations.

fields.summary:
Integrations

Find integrations with GitHub, Hipchat, Flowdock, and Slack in the Settings link at the top of your board.

Priortize Cards

You can prioritze cards by business value, points, or dragging them up or down in the list.
fields.detail:
You can also enter a time estimate and see value/time.

Change how you sort cards with the button. Click the priority button to toggle priority mode.

fields.summary:
Planning Poker

Use planning poker to estimate cards with your team.
fields.detail: Click the Planning Poker button at the top of the card edit window.
